```

---

## Key Learnings

- Merge conflict happens when the same file is modified differently in two branches.  
- Git cannot automatically decide which version should be kept.  
- Git stops merge process and displays conflict markers inside the file.  
- Conflict must be resolved manually by editing the file.  
- After resolution, Git requires staging and committing before completing merge.  
- Conflict resolution is a normal part of collaborative development workflow.  

---

## Real World Use Case

In software development teams, multiple developers may work on the same file simultaneously.

Example:

Developer A changes:

```text
login-button = blue
```

Developer B changes:

```text
login-button = red
```

When merging branches, Git detects both changes and creates conflict.

Developer must manually decide final version.

Example workflow:

```bash
git merge feature-branch
# conflict occurs

notepad file.txt
git add .
git commit -m "resolved conflict"
git push origin main
```

Purpose:

- Prevent accidental overwriting of code changes.

---

## Final Understanding

This task provided practical understanding of one of the most important Git concepts.

Important understanding:

- Conflict happens only when both branches modify the same file differently.  
- Git pauses merge process when automatic merge is not possible.  
- Developer must manually resolve conflict and complete merge process.  

Merge conflict handling is an essential part of real-world software development and team collaboration.

